<p>When you define only one network, what happens if you wanted to take one network address and create six networks from it? You would have to do something called <em>subnetting</em>, because thatâ€™s what allows you to take one larger network and break it into a bunch of smaller networks.
There are loads of reasons if favor of subnetting, including the following benefits:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Reduced network traffic</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Optimized network performance</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Simplified management</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Facilitated spanning of large geographical distances</strong></p>
  </li>
</ul>

